Multimodal Human-Autonomous Agents Interaction Using Pre-Trained Language and Visual Models

Linus Nwankwo and Elmar Rueckert

Paper

arXiv

Data & Resources

GitHub

DOI

License

Abstract

In this paper, we extended the method proposed in [paper] to enable humans to interact naturally with autonomous agents through both spoken and textual conversations. Our extended method exploits the inherent capabilities of pre-trained large language models (LLMs), multimodal visual language models (VLMs), and speech recognition (SR) models to decode the high-level natural language conversation and semantic understanding of the robot's task environment and abstract them to the robot's actionable commands or queries. We performed a preliminary evaluation of our framework's natural vocal conversation understanding with participants from different racial backgrounds and English language accents, using the spoken words as instructional commands to the robot. Quantitatively, we achieved 87.55% vocal command understanding accuracy, 86.27% command execution success, and an average of 0.89 seconds from receiving the users vocal chat commands to initiating the robots actual physical action. The video demonstrations can be found at the project's website, https://osf.io/xxxx.
